Predicting NBA Hall of Fame Status¶

CMSC422 Final Project¶
Fall 2022 Teli¶

Group Members: Prakhar Gupta, Andrew Zhong, Hari Shanmugaraja, Rohit Pasumarthi

Introduction and Motivation¶

The Naismith Memorial Hall of Fame is an honor bestowed upon Basketball players, coaches, and staff that have had exceptional careers or contributions to the game of basketball. In the project, we set out to create predictive models to determine the likelihood of current NBA players achieving Hall of Fame status. We specifically wanted to focus on prediction for players that are currently active or have only recently retired, as they would not be eligible for the award yet. By using statistical models, we are able to gain a less subjective perspective on who belongs in the Hall of Fame, as human decision-making may be swayed by factors such as flashiness or player fame. We hope that the model will be able to highlight players that are deserving of Hall of Fame status, despite not always being in the spotlight or being the most popular players on the most successful teams. Besides using these predictions as a barometer for a players’ greatness (that may otherwise have been passed up due to public popularity), models like these can also be used for more serious reasons, such as for companies to decide which players will be a better bet to sponsor after retirement. We wanted to compare how different models performed against this task, as well as how different models would weight each attribute differently, which would result in different top predictions for Hall of Famers.

In order to handle this and ensure we keep player data separate, we add a player id column to ensure that each player has a unique identifier.

In [9]:
player_data['id'] = player_data.index

We also added a year born column. When computing this from the seasons_stats table we notice that when calculating age by year of play - age for that year, the answers we get are 1 off. Below, we compute the birth year of Michael Jordan and get the year 1964 as our result. If you are an extremely big fan or make a quick Google search, we find that MJ's real birthyear is 1963. This is likely due to the statistics websites taking age at the start of the year, before players have had the chance for their birthdays to pass.

In [10]:
mj_stats = seasons_stats[seasons_stats.Player == 'Michael Jordan*']
mj_stats['Year'].iloc[0] - mj_stats['Age'].iloc[0]
Out[10]:
1964.0

Therefore, we adjust all years born entries down by 1.

In [11]:
seasons_stats['born'] = seasons_stats['Year'] - seasons_stats['Age'] - 1

We now use birth year and player name to join all data, throwing out any records where player born data is missing.

Predicion Models¶

Now that we are done setting up our dataset, we can train various models to predict future hall of fame status for current NBA players, as well as compare how well different models perform against each other. First, we will split our data into training and inference datasets. We only consider players that have been eligible for hall of fame status for long enough or have already achieved hall of fame status to be suitable training data, as otherwise we may get players that have retired recently and are hall of fame-worthy but just haven't had the chance to receive the honor yet. Our inference data is only players that are currently still active or have retired recently and have not yet had the chance to receive hall of fame status.

We then use sklearn's train_test_split function: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.model_selection.train_test_split.html to split our train dataset into train and test subsections for model evaluation purposes.

In [28]:
train = career_num[(career_num.Last_Season <= 1997) | (career_num.HOF == 1)]
test = career_num[(career_num.Last_Season > 1997) & (career_num.HOF == 0)]

X = train.drop('HOF', axis=1)
y = train['HOF']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

X_infer = test.drop('HOF', axis=1)

SVM¶

We first attempted to use an SVM for prediction. We used sklearn's SVM library here: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.svm.SVC.html with the default linear kernel. Since SVMs are extremely powerful at binary classification, we expected and achieved high accuracy on the test dataset. We then used the SVM to produce probabilities for each future HOF-eligible player to achieve HOF status, and sorted players by probability.

In [29]:
svm = SVC(kernel='linear', probability=True)
svm.fit(X_train, y_train)

    "id": test["id"],
    "HOF": svm_y_pred_proba
    })

As you'd expect, successful players like Lebron James, Tim Duncan, and Kobe Bryant were at the top of the HOF list, which goes to show that the SVM model fits our expectations for which current players should be inducted to the Hall of Fame in the future.

Neural Networks¶

When thinking about what models to use for sports prediction, neural networks were a clear choice. Neural networks have been used and have been shown to be potentially effective tools to predict outcomes in sports, and especially basketball. These this study (https://cs230.stanford.edu/projects_winter_2020/reports/32643049.pdf) and (https://www.researchgate.net/publication/24015640_Predicting_NBA_Games_Using_Neural_Networks) are a few examples, just to name a few.

It is common however for neural networks, especially when it comes to deep learning approaches, to be quite large and complex, but let’s see if a small and simple network can be somewhat performant as well. The first step is to come up with an architecture to use. We did not want our architecture to be a bottleneck, so we decided to test out two different model architectures of different philosophies to see if either would have an effect. The first architecture takes the feature space provided and expands it (the first hidden layer is larger than the feature vector) before compressing and the second architecture condenses it to start out with. Both are two-layer neural networks with sigmoid activation functions for the hidden layers and a softmax activation for the output layer.

Before jumping into training our Neural Network, there were some things that needed to be addressed first. This particular use case is a non-standard application of a neural network. We are using historical data that could (and has) change. For example Kobe Bryant was not a Hall of Famer when this data was gathered, but he is now. As a result, we cannot really have a test dataset. We are simply training the model on past data and asking it to pick data points it would think to be most similar. As a result, we have no way of telling if the model is overfit with this approach.

We noticed that the number of Hall of Famers in the dataset was only 74, or a little over 7% of the total represented athletes. We were worried that the low percentage of Hall of Famers would lead to the neural nets overfitting. We created some code to add noised data of Famers to prevent this, but the addition may have actually made the overfitting worse as the final confidences were much higher, so we took it back out. Each feature of the data was then standardized and we dropped the ID and last_season fields so that the neural network wouldn’t just memorize which IDs and ending years correspond to Hall of Famers.

def gen_noised_true():
    true_examples = career_num[career_num.HOF > 0].drop(["id", "Last_Season", "HOF"], axis = 1)
    for col in true_examples.columns:
        noise = np.random.normal(0,true_examples[col].std()/10, size=true_examples[col].shape)
        true_examples[col] = true_examples[col] + noise
    return true_examples

We then started to play around with the hyperparameters. We found that the loss for the neural networks stopped decreasing greatly after 5 epochs, so we decided to stop the training there to prevent further overfitting. (The confidence for 10 epochs was really high). A batch size of 32 also lead to a reproducable and smooth decrease in loss.

Neural Network Conclusion¶

Overall, we see that the output of the networks matches up greatly with the other models we have trained. While this is promising, it is hard to tell just how well this model will extrapolate to even more data. Also unlike the other models, the results of the networks vary depending on how the weights were initialized (although most of the recognizable names are still there reliably). As aforementioned, these models were designed to be simple on purpose. Most neural network approaches when it comes to sports science use deep learning, and as this Medium article explains, it is never just a “classification problem” (https://towardsdatascience.com/machine-learning-for-sports-betting-not-a-basic-classification-problem-b42ae4900782). The approach we took to training the other models is also not the approach that is the most appropriate for training the neural networks, and going forward finding more data and creating a different training paradigm may lead to verifiably better results.

Looking at our end results for the decision tree, we can see that while we do get a result for who will and who will not be in the Hall of Fame, these results don't give us anything that can be used beyond just 'yes' or 'no'. With the other classifiers, we get a percentage chance for Hall of Fame status, which is a much more useful metric to evaluate who potential Hall of Famers. Simply know whether or not some can make it to the Hall of Fame will not help a company choose a potential player to sponsor, whereas knowing a player has 92% chance to make it to the Hall of Fame definitely will help a company choose. This goes to show that not all classifiers are going to provide results that matter for all types of problems. In this case, while a decision tree does the job, it just doesn't perform at the same level as the three other algorithms, because there's no way to really compare the results from the Decision Tree.

For further reading into why Decision Trees are not optimal, the link:( https://careerfoundry.com/en/blog/data-analytics/what-is-a-decision-tree/#:~:text=Disadvantages%20of%20decision%20trees,-Overfitting%20(where%20a&text=They%20are%20not%20well%2Dsuited,path%20includes%20many%20chance%20variables. ), was very informative for me when I was trying to interpret the results of the decision tree.

KNN¶

To run the KNN model, we took a look at KNeighborsClassifer from the sklearn library. After analysis and testing of prediction percentage on the number of neighbors helps classify, we found that 22 neighbors was a prediction that got enough of the neighbors to make an accurate prediction

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=22)

Similar to the other models, we decided that we will have the training data of players who stopped playing 20 years ago based on the last data year, which was 2017. The players represented in the test data are those who are either playing or recently retired

By gaining high percentage chances with the top 10 players having over 80% confidence of making the Hall of Fame, we can say that using the KNN model is beneficial in using analytics as a measure of success, rather than only the eye test.

An article that helped give us more perspective and growth towards modeling and predictions in the NBA is: https://medium.com/kenyon-college-sports-analytics/using-knn-methods-to-predict-cavs-outcomes-based-on-halftime-data-b809b2d47ae6 which covered how by using KNN, it would be possible to add addtional confidence in stats and game scores on certain games.

Conclusion¶

All models that we used were able to make similar predictions, with a great deal of overlap in the top predictions for Hall of Famers by the SVM, Neural Network, and K Nearest Neighbors models. This supports the idea that each of these models produce accurate predictions on the likelihood of a player’s induction into the Hall of Fame and is a strong vote of confidence for these top players. Since the model predictions also match our expectations for Hall of Famers as well as recent Hall of Fame inductees, we also know that the models produce very accurate predictions for Hall of Famers given the stats. As a possible extension to our work, we would like to investigate whether or not we can predict Hall of Fame status early in an NBA player’s career. This would provide much more helpful information for companies, teams, and fans as they would be able to get an idea of how successful a player will be in the future, instead of after their career is already over.

Future Work¶

In future work, we would like to further investigate the relationships between the models. For example, we would like to know which features are most strongly correlated with the difference in the model predictions; i.e. do certain models weigh a given feature more heavily than others, and are therefore more likely to predict different players? We would also like to consider applying data augmentation techniques; while there are hundreds of Hall of Fame inductees over time, there is still a relatively small number of them especially with respect to the total all-time NBA player base as a whole. With data augmentation, we could generate artificial “new” data which could potentially improve the robustness of our prediction models. Finally, we are also curious about the potential applications of similar models to other sports. For example, baseball is another sport with a great deal of publicly available statistics (e.g https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/open-source-sports/baseball-databank). We could apply the same techniques to other sports and make similar predictions.
